{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/0028060057A/1930102401/0528.xml":{"full_text":"A-8\n(THE EVENING STAR\nWith Sunday Morning Edition.\nWASHINGTON, D. C.\nFRIDAY October 24, 1930\nTHEODORE W. NOTES... .Editor\nThe Evening Star Newspaper Company\nBusiness office:\n__ llth. St. and Pennsylvania Are.\nHew York Office: 110 East 42nd St.\nChicago Office: Lake Michigan Bulldii.g.\nEuropean Office: 14 Resent St., London.\nEngland.\nRate by Carrier Within the City.\nThe Evening Star .46c per month\nffie Evening end Sunday Star\n(when 4 Sundays) 60c per month\nThe Evening and Sunday Star\n(when 5 Sundays) BSc r>er month\nThe Sunday Star 6c per copy\nCollection made at the end of *aeh month.\nOrders may be sent In by mail or telephone\nHAtional 5000.\nRate by Mail\u2014Payable in Advance.\nMaryland and Virginia.\nSally and Sunday 1 yr.. *10.00: 1 mo.. 85c\nally only. 1 yr.. 88.00; 1 mo.. 50c\nunday only 1 yr- *4.00; 1 mo.. 40c\nAll Other States and Canada.\nDally and Sunday. .1 yr.. *l2 00; Imo.tl 00\nDally only. I yr.. *8.00: 1 mo., 76c\nSunday only 1 yr., *5.00: 1 mo.. 50c\nMember of the Associated Press.\nThe Associated Press ,1s exclusively entitled\nto the use for republication of all news dis\npatches credited to It or not otherwise cred\nited in this paper and also the local news\npublished herein. All rights of publication of\napeclal dispatches herein are also rererved.\nProducing the Facts.\nWith commendable foresight the\nBureau of Efficiency is preparing in ad\nvance for the fiscal inquiry this Winter\nby revising its 1929 table concerning\nFederal and local participation in\nfinancing the Capital. The bureau has\nreceived no request from the Mapes\nsubcommittee that this be done, but it\nla reasonable to suppose that no in\nquiry can be considered complete with\nout the valuable data compiled by the\nbureau\u2019s investigators, and they will be\ncalled for sooner or later.\nInteresting light is shed on the bu\nreau\u2019* revision of its 1929 figures by a\nrecent article in The Star which showed\nthat the Government's recent pur\nchases In the so-called Avenue trian\ngle have been Included In the new es\ntimates of Federal tax-exempt holdings\nin the District. The value of land\n\u2022lone in this area, according to an as\naesament valuation furnished by As\naessor Richards, amounts to $17,000,000,\nwhile the improvements are greatly in\nexcess of this amount. Thus, applying\nthe bureau's formula for measuring the\nFederal Government\u2019s debt to the Dis\ntrict \u201cas a municipal taxpayer,\u201d the\nfictitious amount set down as tax rev\nenues owing from Uncle Sam would be\nmaterially Increased by the Govern\nment\u2019s large purchases of land and im\nprovements. In the' last report, this\ntax\u2014including personalty and intangi\nbles \u2014amounted to $7,440,939, but the\nbureau\u2019s new figures are expected to\nraise this amount well over a million\ndollars. As the Government land pur\nchases since 1928 have not been con\nfined to the Avenue triangle, it is rea\nsonable to suppose that the Bureau of\nEfficiency has Included other land, upon\nwhich to assess the Federal Govern\nment\u2019s real estate taxes, and the land\nIn the triangle.\nThe point of Interest to the District,\nhowever. Is not the amount that Is due\nfrom the Federal Government merely\nas a municipal taxpayer. For obvious\nreasons It Is impossible to construe the\nFederal Government\u2014which possesses\nthe exclusive right of legislation\u2014mere\nly as a municipal taxpayer. And the\ndifficulty of properly assessing the in\ntangibles of the Federal Government\nere apparent. But granting, for the\npurposes of the bureau\u2019s survey, that\nthe municipal tax owing the District\nby the Federal Government will now\n\u2022mount to figure approximating\n$8,500,000, the balance between this and\nthe $9,500,000 which represented the\nFederal Government\u2019s contribution last\nyear la reduced to a million dollars.\nThe Bureau of Efficiency has prop\nerly maintained that the Federal Gov\nernment\u2019s Just contribution to the\nCapital might be found by first com\nputing the sum owing to the District\nas a municipal taxpayer, and, secondly,\nby computing the amount owing to the\nDistrict by reason of the extraordinary\nexpenditures of the District occasioned\nby the fact that Washington is the\nNation's capital. Needless to say, there\nwas never any attempt on the part of\nCongress to compute this second\namount. But if it was represented by\nthe difference between the lump sum\nand the $7,440,939 in fictitious Federal\ntaxes paid the District, it would have\nbeen about a million and a half dollar*.\nThe bureau's new figures will probably\nreduce this balance to about a million\nglollars, which would demand at least\nhalf-million dollar increase in the\nlump sum above the $9,500,000 allowed\nlast year.\nOs course, the Federal Government's\ndebt to the DUtrict on account of the\nlarge expenditures occasioned by the\nfaet that this Is the Capital exceeds a\nmillion and a half dollars. The point\nIs that every investigation, impartially\nundertaken, will produce the facts that\nJustify and demand an increase in the\nFederal contribution. Members of the\nHouse accepted the Bureau of Effi\nciency's report last time by emphasizing\none half of it and ignoring the other\nhalf. It will be enlightening to see how\nthey accept the forthcoming report,\nwhich, studied in any light, shows an\nIncreased contribution to Capital main\ntenance and development due from the\nFederal Government.\nOne church recruit costs ten times\nas much to enroll as one Army recruit,\naccording to statements made at a na\ntional church conference now in ses\nsion in Milwaukee. Possibly ha is worth\nthat much more.\nThe World Situation.\n\"Misery loves company.\u201d\nThat is about all the comfort to be\nderived from the review of world busi\nness conditions which came yesterday\nfrom the Department of Commerce,\nbased on cable snd radio dispatches\nfrom agents all over the earth. From\nNew Zealand to Western Europe there\nis business depression, unemployment\nand hardship. Where there are good\ncrops prices are so low that the grow\ners cannot profit from the bounty of\nnature. It all goes to show that there\n\u2022re underlying causes of the depression\nwhich affect all nations. It is a world\nconcern. What these causes are is\nanother matter. They are buried deep\nly in the complexity of economic forces.\nWhile they remain active, however,\nthe disease will not be cured. The local\nsymptoms may be made to disappear\ntemporarily, but they are likely to ap\npear again and again so long aa the\nfundamental maladjustment remain*.\nEventually, of course, this will cure\nitself\u2014which is not of any immediate\ncomfort to the patient. Already, the\nDepartment of Commerce finds, there\ni are hopeful signs in some places.\nBut a hopeful phase of the whole\nsituation is that It now is possible to\nsecure such a detailed world picture.\nIt is a primary requisite for a correct\ndiagnosis. The more detailed it is the\nsounder basis it offers for study in the\nstatistical laboratory. It is at least cer\ntain that the problem is not simple,\nto be solved by Inspirations or guesses.\nThe world is an economic whole, its\nlife forces delicately balanced. Every\nyear it is becoming more and more\norganized. Its parts more and more\ninterdependent. A slight maladjust\nment anywhere may throw the whole\neconomic organism out of balance. Na\ntions can no longer live as independent\nwholes. For that matter, they never\ncould; but hitherto the fact has not\nbeen so obvious.\nPerhaps depression spreads over the\nworld purely by the psychological\nmechanism of suggestion and the\nactual situation is a fulfillment of fears,\nrather than any organic ill of the\nearth. But it is more comforting to\nbelieve in something specific which\ncan be found and remedied, rather than\nin a vague generality which is to be\ntreated by other generalities. In any\nevent there is a real advance toward\nunderstanding in this comprehensive\nview of the total situation which could\nnever come from considering the phe\nnomenon circumscribed by national\nlines.\nThe Five-Year Plan.\n\u201cDeprecatory dispatches and purring\nplatitudes\u2019\u2019 'to the contrary notwith\nstanding\u2014to use Dr. Edmund A. Walsh\u2019s\nalliterative phrase\u2014Soviet Russia's now\ncelebrated five-year plan is a project,\npure and simple, for furthering Com\nmunism\u2019s plot for world revolution. The\nbrilliant regent of Georgetown Univer\nsity's Foreign Service School has just\nInaugurated In Washington his sixth\nsuccessive series of public lectures on\nRussia. No man in America speaks\nwith more knowledge pr authority on\nthat subject. Dr. Walsh is performing\na national service in keeping the search\nlight turned in the direction of Moscow's\nsleepless maneuverlngs for achieving an\n\u201cinternational dictatorship of the pro\nletariat.\u201d\nThe lecturer reminds us of something\nlittle understood in this country. No\nsingle act of the Soviet government,\nwhich is the creature of the Commu\nnist party and \u201cdirected\" by it, accord\ning to \u201cCzar\" Stalin\u2019s own admissions\nto an American labor delegation, is con\nceived or carried out except with an eye\nupon its international effect. The\nautocrats of the Kremlin incessantly\nand Invariably have \u201cworld revolution\"\nIn mind. That, like all their other\nprograms, is the underlying purpose of\nthe five-year-plan for high-pressuring\nthe \u201cUnion of Soviet Socialist Repub\nlics\u2019\u2019 into the production by the end of\n1933 of the fabulous total of $42,000,-\n000,000 worth of industrial and agri\ncultural produce.\nDr. Walsh depicts this Utopian\nproject as masking Stalin\u2019s \u201cretreat,\u201d\njust as Lenin resorted to the \u201cNep\u201d\n\u2014new economic policy\u2014to cover the\nfailure of the Soviet's earlier economic\nvagaries. The- Georgetown publicist\nventures no prophecy as to the outcome\nof the five-year plan. If It should fail,\nit Is obvious that Communistic hopes\nof world revolution would suffer a\ncrash from which they could not easily\nbe revived. The success of the wildest\nexperiment In economic history would,\non the other hand, as unquestionably\nbolster up Red visions of eventual con\nquest of \u201ccapitalism.\u201d\nPolice Conrtesy.\nThe prompt and drastic action taken\nby the Police Trial Board in the case of\nan officer who was accused of being dis\ncourteous and profane to a motorist\nshould have a salutary effect on the\nfew remaining browbeating, \u201ctough\"\npolicemen In the department. Charged\nwith engaging In an argument about a\ntraffic violation with the motorist be\ncause he claimed that the driver \u201cirritat\ned\u201d him, the policeman, on the recom\nmendation of his superiors, was haled\nbefore the Trial Board, promptly con\nvicted and dismissed from the force.\nIt was a refreshing case of quick justice.\nGen. Crosby and Maj. Pratt have\nbeen striving for courtesy and efficiency\nin the Police Department. In order\nto promote these attributes in the men\nan honor roll was recently Inaugurated\nwhich not only gave special recognition\nto those who deserved it, but a five\ndollar-a-month increase in salary. At\nthe same time it was announced that\noffenders of the courtesy rule would\nfind no sympathy with their actions.\nThe action of the Trial Board in this\ncase makes the campaign even more\neffective In that It will serve as a warn\ning to the minority of policemen who\nstill believe tthat when they don the uni\nform they are the monarchs of all they\nsurvey and can \"get away\u201d with any\nthing so far as the public is concerned.\nIt should not take many more Incidents\nof this sort to stamp out the practice\naltogether.\nThe funeral of Gen. Weyler was\nextremely simple There are still liv\ning snipers of forty years ago who\nwould have been overjoyed to help him\nget full military honors.\nWhat I\u00bb Its Future?\nThe glistening white stone of Pepco\u2019s\nnew plant at Tenth and E streets and\nthe dull, somber walls of old \u201cFord\u2019s\nTheater\" provide an interesting study\nIn contrast between the modern office\nstructure and a building that slxty\neight years ago was regarded as one\nof the finest in town. Progress is gradu\nally surrounding the theater, but It\nstill remains isolated by the grim and\ntragic record of its past. What is to\nbe done with it? How long will it stand\nthere?\nAcross the street the Peterson house,\nin which Lincoln died and which has\nbecome more famous still because of\nthe Oldroyd Museum, has been pre\nserved by Government purchase and\nwill perhaps continue for many yean\nas a sort of patriotic shrine, visited by\n1 thousands of Americans. But Ford's is\ni closed, empty and dark, filled only with\nthe memories of death.\nThe building was three yean old\nwhen Lincoln was assassinated, and it\n1 remained closed after the tragedy for\nr nearly eight years. Opened asain in\n187$ and known both as Ford\u2019s and as\ni \u201cWall\u2019s Opera House,\u201d It regained popu\nferity at one of the Capital\u2019s leadini\nTHE EVENIN'** STAR, WASHINGTON, D. C. t FRIDAY, OCTOBER 24, 1930.\ntheaters and, during that oecadt at\nleast, retained It. Purchased by the\nGovernment, it was used for the Adju\ntant General's Office, but on the morn\ning of June 9, 1893, a great part of\nthe roof and inner structure collapsed,\nkilling outright or fatally injuring\ntwenty-two persons. It has been used\nsince as Government office building,\nstore house and recruiting station, but\nin the last few years has been occupied\nonly by watchmen. When the Pepco\nfoundations were being dug there was\ndanger that the south wall of the Ford\nbuilding might cave in, but adequate\nprecautions prevented that.\nVarious legislative proposals have\nbeen made for disposing of the build\ning. One recent bill was to make it\na club house for veterans. But it is\ndifficult to believe that it can ever serve\nany useful purpose. It only perpetuates\ntragic memories and is hardly worth\nsaving. Its appeal, after all, is more\nto morbid curiosity than to any real\nsentiment.\nThe Stage.\nEvery now and then, for the' past\nquarter of a century, some one has\nv arisen to state that the stage is in no\ndanger of extinction at the hands of\nthe \u201cmovies.\u201d Miss Ethel Barrymore,\ndistinguished and beloved actress, is the\nlatest champion.\n\u201cThe people are hungry for the thea\nter,\u201d Miss Barrymore said. There can\nbe no gainsaying that she is right. The\nlove for the theater is instinct in all\npeoples; the only question is whether the\nso-called \u201clegitimate stage\u201d can con\ntinue in the face of competition aided\nby the inventive genius of man.\nAt the present it appears to compe\ntent observers that it can. Although\nstage craft is essentially the same today\nas it was when Euripides wrote, hu\nman nature is the same, too.\nThe human voice is the same, and\n1 the powers of personal attraction are\nthe stune. Miss Barrymore represents\nboth phases. There are many lovers of\nthe drama who are willing to believe\nthat as long as the theater presents\nsuch players there will t>e no particular\ndanger of the extinction of the legiti\nmate stage.\nAlways In the background of human\nthought and action lies the rebound,\nor the return to U?e old. The playgoing\nworld may hustle mainly to the \"talkies\"\nat this period, for they are new. Inter\nesting, breezy, but as surely as the\nstage keeps to the human heart and\nmind, theatergoers will incline to re\nturn to it, and keep it a living force\nin a land which d&mlres human per\nsonality.\nNotables arriving In Abyssinia for\nthe approaching coronation are wel\ncomed by official bands playing the\nproper respective national anthems. It\nis not known how good brass bands of\nthat country are, but it is a fairly good\nbet that some of the arrivals would\nhave preferred the Abyssinian maid\nplaying on her dulcimer, described by\nColeridge.\nOs all brands of criminals the fire\nbug probably gets more actual enjoy\nment out of his offense than any other.\nAnd those who have the sentencing of\nhim should remember to make him pay\nwell for his fun.\nEthel Barrymore declares that the\npublic is hungry for stage plays. Sure,\nbut, as on any restaurant menu, those\n$4.40 and higher items make one stop,\nconsider and order beans.\nGeneral, aged and stately monarch\nof the city park buffalo herd of Den\nver, has passed on. When he gets to\nwherever good buffaloes go, he will have\nplenty of company.\nA jury panel struck by a flock of\nchallenges is about as thorough a wreck\nas is a door panel riddled by a load\nof buckshot.\nSHOOTING STARS.\nBY PHILANDER JOHNSON.\nThe Ambitious Oyster.\nThe oyster In his narrow bed\nComplained about his lot.\n\u201cI fain would see the world,\u201d he said,\n\u201cAnd leave this humble spot.\nI\u2019ve heard of places where the lights\nAre burned till 1 a.m.\nBy people out to view the sights.\nI would I were with them.\u201d\nHe had his wish. They lifted him\nUp from his briny lair.\nHe saw the lights\u2014then all grew dim\u2014\nThey served him up with care.\nAnd as his shell from him they tore\nThese words\u2014his last\u2014he spoke:\n\u201cI would that I were back once more\nIn dear old Pocomoke!\u201d\nOh, youth, with vague ambitious fired,\nDespise not simple Joy.\nThe things which most you have desired,\nOnce gained, may moat annoy I\n1 Your fat* you cannot well foresee.\nSome are\u2014tha fcvored few\u2014\nThe epicures. And some must be\nThe oysters in the stew.\nA Risk.\n\u201cWhy don\u2019t you do something philan\nthropic?\u201d\n\"I\u2019m afraid to,\u201d answered Senator\nSorghum. \u201cIf I show that I have any\nmoney beyond my actual needs, aome\nbody will be asking where I got it.\u201d\ni\nForethought.\n\u201cWhat did you do about those col\nonizers that conspired to corrupt the\ni ballot of Crimson Gulch?\u201d\n1 \u201cWe held \u2019em till the census could\ni be took,\u201d answered Piute Pete; \u201can\u2019\nr then turned \u2019em over to the law an\u2019 fcr\nder committee.\u201d\nSimilarity.\nThis world Is a tumultuous scene\nAnd our attentive care it claims\nTo tell the difference between\nElections, fights and foot ball games.\nPaternal Pride.\n\"Do you approve of your son\u2019s engag\ning in foot ball?\u201d\n\u201cWell,\u201d answered Farmer Corntossel,\n\u201cI don\u2019t exactly approve of it. But I\nj don\u2019t feel nigh as annoyed as I would\ns be If I thought he wasn\u2019t able to hold\nf his own in the scrimmage.\nA Race-Track Sentiment.\nWe wonder if the odds were fair,\nE\u2019en when we wm a bet;\nt Though luck is good, we still declare\nr It should be better yet.\na \u201cI generally finds.\u201d said Uncle Eben,\ns \"dat de man dat\u2019s got sense enough to\ntake my good advice la too busy workia*\ng out his own plans to Uitgp to it.\u201d\n.mJfHiik: A\nTHIS AND THAT\nBY CHARLES E. TRACEWELL.\nHow do people read physically?\nThe favbrite reading positions are\nsitting and reclining, the former in\nchairs, the latter in beds.\nThe great bulk of readers read In one\nof these positions, sanctioned by long\nusage and common sense.\nA few stand up to read, others sprawl\non the floor on their elbows, after the\ntraditional manner attributed to Abra\nham Lincoln.\nMost booklovers are inclined to make\nthemselves as comfortable as possible\nwhile engaged in their favorite recrea\ntion.\nSome one has said that one cf the\nfactors involved In the popularity of\nmotoring is that it is indulged in while\nsitting down.\nThe same may be said of reading.\nPerhaps 75 per cent of known readers\nsit in chairs. It is at once the easiest,\nthe most natural, and, all matters taken\ninto consideration, the best way.\nHe or she who loves to read may\ndo so at a longer stretch in a chair\nthan in bed. Every one who has tried\nit knows the disadvantage of the latter\nmethod. One grows'sleepy!\n\nEven too comfortable a chair is some\nthing of a handicap, especially at night,\nthe favorite reading time of the Nation,\nand especially after dinner, when diges\ntion makes its demands on the blood.\nBoth alimentary and intellectual\ndigestion depend upon the blood stream.\nIf the call of the stomach exoeeds that\nof the brain, the reader will find him\nself growing confused before he has\ngone through three chapters, even if\nthey be short ones.\nIt is questionable, therefore., whether\neven a head rest is best in one\u2019s favo\nrite reading chair. The natural reading\nposition is one of ease, muscles relaxed,\nwith the head bent somewhat over the\nbook, and therefore needing no rest.\nNo doubt too much stress was placed\nformerly upon the necessity for a\nstraight back. It is a difficult position\nto maintain while reading, in fact is\nnot called for by the very exigencies of\nthe case.\nElevated feet are another moot ques\ntion. In the privacy of one\u2019s own home,\nthere is no real reason why one should\nnot place his feet upon another chair,\nIf he does not mind spoiling the chair,\nand so long as he does not make him\nself obnoxious to some other person.\nMen take to the elevated-feet posi\ntion naturally enough, in reading a\nfavorite detective story. If they sup\nplement it with a pipe, their reading\nposture is excellent, from all practical\nconsiderations, if not for appearance\u2019\n\"bunking\u201d of one\u2019s crullers into one\u2019s\ncoffee is certainly not a very elevating\nsight, for some reason or other, but\nthose who do it find It a satisfactory\nmethod of eating.\n\nThe trouble with reclining, of course,\nis that one is inclined to go to sleep.\nEven the most exciting story finds the\ncompetition with sleep an unfair one.\nBut if one can keep awake, reading\nin bed is very comfortable. Perhaps\nthe best way is to prop one\u2019s self up\nwith pillows; and therefore to read sit\nting up, after all.\nThe warmth and quiet of bed, how\never, has its somnolent qualities. It is\ndifficult to keep from nodding. In j\nsuch an emergency a favorite trick is to\nWASHINGTON OBSERVATIONS\nBY FREDERIC WILLIAM WILE.\nThat the Hoover administration is i\nthe paramount issue ip the 1930 cam-\npaign has always been' the claim of the\nDemocratic National Committee. But it\nhas remained for Claude O. Bowers,\nHouston Convention keynoter, to give\nopen and official utterance to that view.\nThe New York editor-historian broad\ncast last night a frontal attack on the\nHoover regime under the title of \u201cThe\nCollapse of an Administration.\" The\nRepublicans resolutely refuse to accept\nthe President and his record as issues\nin a purely congressional campaign.\nThey contend that the time' to put\n.Hooverlsm on trial before the bar of\npublic opinion will be 1932. The\nachievements or failures of a O. O. P.\nCongress, say Messrs. Peas, Lucas, Wat\nson, Moses et al., are the things, and\nthe only things, on which the voters, in\nelecting a new House and Senate, should\nbe called upon to express judgment.\n\nEvidently President Hoover's refusal\nto intrude himself into the campaign\u2014\nGifford Pinchot to the contrary not\nwithstanding\u2014is based on this theory.\nIt is, nevertheless, a fact that in count\nless House and Senate fights all over\nthe country Republican candidates\nhaven\u2019t hesitated to .trot out their\n\u201csupport of the administration\" as a\ngood reason for giving them return\ntickets. As far as anybody knows, Mr.\nHoover has confined his \u201cinterference\u201d\nin the campaign to two instances. Early\nin the game he wrote a letter to a Ten\nnessee Republican member of the House\nof Representatives publicly thanking\nhim for supporting the White House on\nMuscle Shoals legislation. After Dwight\nMorrow\u2019s primary contest\u2014if that is\nthe word\u2014the President let it be known\nthat he hoped New Jersey would honor\nitself by sending \u201cLindy\u2019s\" father-in\nlaw to the Senate. The Hoover view,\nin a nutshell, is that the 1930 cam\npaign is not his baby and that from\nevery standpoint it would be injudi\ncious for him to assume its fatherhood.\n\nIn a day or two two more of our\nEuropean Ambassadors Walter E.\nEdge, from Paris, and Irwin B. Laugh\nlln, from Madrid \u2014will be in Wash\nington to commune with the President\nand the Secretary of State. Though\nUncle Sam Is not directly involved in\nany of the Old World\u2019s sorely troubled\naffairs, the universal me?s \u201cover there\"\nbristles with issues and possibilities\nwhich might at almost any moment\ndemand our vigorous interest. Fred\neric M. Sackett, American Ambassador\nto Germany, has just concluded a visit\nin Washington. The White House and\nState Department got from the Ken\ntucky diplomat their first close-up of\ndevelopments in the Reich, as viewed\nby our official observer at Berlin. Mr.\nr Sackett is a bull, not a bear, on Ger\nmany\u2019s future.\naa a a\nAnybody who wants to know ex\nactly the genesis and status of the\nUnited States\u2019 interest in Palestine can\nderive a world of information from\na State Department pamphlet. It\u2019s\nentitled \u201cThe Palestine Mandate Con\nvention\" and contains the full docu\ni mentary record of our negotiations\nwith Great Britain for a treaty guar\nanteeing American rights in the Holy\nLand. Readers of the pamphlet will\nencounter a disclosure of which hardly\none in a million Americans has knowl\nedge. In January, 1922, during the\nWashington Armament Conference,\nLord (then Mr.) Balfour, who headed\nthe British delegation, urged Secre\ntary Hughes to give early considera\ntion to the Palestine treaty. In a\nletter to Hughes Balfour said: \u201cAt\nthe Paris Peace Conference I always\nwarmly advocated that the Palestine\nmandate should be undertaken, not by\nBritain, but by the United States.\nThough subsequent events have shown\nme that such a policy would never\nr have commended itself to the Ameri\ncan people. I still think that, so far\n1 as the Middle East is concerned, it\n1 would have been the best.\"\n\nTwo distinguished members of the\nWashington diplomatic corps\u2014Ambas\nsador von Prittwltz of Germany and\nMinister Wu of China\u2014have just re\nturned to their posts after protracted\nabsences. Dr. von Prittwit* ends a\nthree months\u2019 leave in his fatherland,\nand Dr. Wu is back from a long siege\nof duty as China\u2019s principal delegate\nto the League of Nations. The German\n3 Ambassador was on the high seas while\n1 the new Reichstag was sustaining the\nHindenburg-Bruenlag cabinet by sub\nrecline on the side, with the book held\nwith one hand.\nIn this position sleep always wins,\nno matter who the author of the book\nmay be. Hours later the reader wakes,\nthe light still burning, the book still\nopen. With blinking eyes he goes\nto sleep in earnest, having read at the\nmost half a chapter.\nYet for the person of steadfast de\ntermination, who is able to keep awake,\nreading in bed is one of the most de\nlightful modes\n\nIn bed one may eat as well as read.\nEating, with some natures, is syn\nonymous with reading.\nCandy, crackers, chocolate and apples\n\u2014these are the favored foodstuffs for\nbed reading.\nThey may be utilized, of course, rnd\nquite often are, in sittmg reading, but\nsomehow seem to fit in better with\nreading in bed.\nCracker crumbs, for instance, getting\nbetween the sheets, are guaranteed to\nkeep any reader from falling asleep be\nfore the last chapter is finished.\nChocolates have a nice, smeary way\nof getting on the bedclothes.\nAnimal crackers are a lavorite.\nApples have no standing with con\nfirmed bedtime readers, and should be\nleft to cruder souls.\n\nSome men read standing vp, but they\nare heroes.\nLincoln must have berti made of\nstern stuff. Indeed, to have placed him\nself of his own free will on his stomach\nand-elbows while reading bis Bible and\nShakespeare. Occasionally one will see\na limber child doing it now, but not\noften. It was a pioneer method\nAs for standing up while reading,\nthere is no point to It, except in certain,\ncases, known of old, when sitting down\nwas an unthinkable process. Surely\none must be comfortable while leading\na book. The mind, at its best, is easily\ndistracted. One finds an occasions*\nj volume, every now and then, which\nholds the attention despite all Induce\nments to the contrary, but these are\nthe rare books, and differ with every\nindividual.\nMost books have their dull places,\npages which must be waded through\nwith determination, if not with zest.\nThe going is hard, but the end is in\nsight; soon the hero will appear and\nall will be well again.\nBut if one\u2019s foot goes to sleep, for\nInstance, the hero will never appear\u2014\nat least not that evening. Banging\ndoors, radio music, spell defeat to many\na reader, although there are others\nwho say that they read better for thd\nlatter.\nWell, maybe they do, but one who Is\nnot so constructed, mentally, may be\nforgiven for feeling that one neither\nlistens very well nor reads very well\nunder such conditions. Good reading\ndemands concentration, and concentra\ntion, except unde; unusual conditions,\nrequires some degree of quiet. Libraries\nhave not made silence a decree to show\nthe authority of librarians, but simply\nbecause it gives the best atmosphere\nfor serious reading.\nThe best position for reading, there\nfore, is the one which best suits you,\nthe reader. If you like to throw one leg\nover the arm of your chair, by all\nmeans do so. If there is any objec\ntion, say that Mark Twain lead so. He\ni didn't, of course, but he wrote in bed,\nso that should settle the matter.\nstantial vote- of confidence. Berlin\u2019s\nenvoy to the United States points to that\nresult as prima facie evidence that \u201cthe\nGerman nation is not inclined to have\nits destiny decided by a certain group\nof extremists.\" Dr. Wu at Geneva was\nparticularly concerned with the League's\ncrusade to curb the narcotics traffic.\nHe presented a resolution requesting\ncertain data and information as to the\ndrug traffic in that country. Dr. Wu\ndeclares it is common knowledge that\n\u201ccertain governments\u201d might exert\ngreater vigilance in control of narcotics\nin the East. Foreign supplies of heroin I\nand morphine, he charges, are doing\nvastly more damage in China than her\nown opium traffic.\n\nIt is a striking tribute to the public\nappetite for facts about Soviet Russia\nthat the Rev. Dr. Edmund A. Walsh of\nGeorgetown University should still be\npacking one of Washington's biggest\nauditoriums with a lecture series on\nthat subject. Last night Dr. Walsh de\nlivered his sixtieth consecutive address\non Russia in five years. His audiences\npromise to be bigger and more inter\nested than ever in his authoritative ex\nposure of Communism's plans for world\nrevolution. The distinguished Jesuit is\ndevoting his early talks this season to\nan explanation of the \u201cfive-year plan\u201d\nfor manufacturing <42,000,000,000 of\nindustrial and agricultural wealth in\nRussia by the end of 1933 through\nhigh-pressure methods.\n\nMrs. Emily Newell Blair of Missouri,\nwell known former vice chairman of\nthe Democratic National Committee\nand a pioneer suffragist, has embarked\nupon a crusade evidently designed to wean\nher sex away from politics and back to\nthe nursery, the kitchen and the living\nroom. \u201cFeminism.\u201d she Intimates, has\nhad its day, largely because it cannot\nhold out against the odds which in\nequality between men and women pre\nsents. As a result, Mrs. Blair sees a\nrecrudescence of homemaking. She\u2019s\njust written a book in which her views\nare persuasively ventilated, \u201cThe Crea\ntion of the Home.\u201d Incidentally, the\ndynamic daughter of Joplin is herself\nleading a quadruple life\u2014wife, mother,\npolitician and writer.\n(Copyright. 1930.)\nBritain Will Review\nSecession Problems\nFrom the New York Herald Tribune.\nThose subjects of the British Empire\nwho are ignorant of America and its\nways are sometimes told byway of\nexplanation that it is unsafe to gener\nalize about this country because of its\nsize and its heterogeneity. To make\nthe point clear they are told that the\nterm \u201cAmerican\u201d may be held to cor\nrespond to \u201cBritisher,\" whereas such a\nterm as \u201cMiddle .Westerner\u201d or \u201cNew\nEnglander\u201d corresponds to such terms\nas \u201cEnglish\u201d or \u201cIrish\u201d or \u201cAustralian.\u201d\nAmerica, in truth, is not quite so large\nand diverse as the British Empire or the\nformer Russian Empire, but it Is cer\ntainly much farther removed from the\nEuropean concept of a nation. From\nthe broad standpoint of political struc\nture, we are certainly nearer the Union\nof Soviet Republics than we are to\nthe Republic of France.\nBecause we are a Union of sovereign\nStates we may take more than a casual\ninterest in some of the remarks being i\nmade in London on the eve of the im\nperial conference. The question of se-'\ncession is rniuch to the fore. To the\nNationalists of India, of course, this is\na very burning question indeed. If not\nquite so acute, it is certainly interest\ning to the Irish Free State and the Un\nion of South Africa. Gen. Hertzog, the\nprime minister of the South African\nynton, has very definite views. He is\nquoted. \u201cNot a jot or a tittle of our\nindependence will be sacrificed. I am\nnot going to the conference to get con\nfirmation of the union\u2019s right to secede.\nThat right is above speculation.\nLike ourselves, the British know a\ngood deal about the principle of fed\neration. Moreover, the Union of South\nAfrica would lose not a little by cut\nting itself away. The dispatches indi\ncate that a naval review of impressive\nproportions will be held for the benefit\nof the imperial delegates. The sight\nof the fleet may make some delegates\nthink twice before they give up a pro\ntection which haejneant much to them\nand which costs tfttem so little.\n4\nNew Banking Law Urged\nSavings Deposit Accounts Held\nLiabilities to National Banks.\nTo the Editor ot The 8t\u00bbr:\nWhen the special session of Congress\nwas convened to revise the tariff\u2014\nalready 20 per cent too high\u2014and\nwasting 11 months at the job, the\nwriter pointed out that that was not\nthe cause of the business depression,\nsince the exports to foreign countries\ngreatly exceeded Imports, resulting In\nthe United States accumulating nearly\nhalf the gold of the world, but that the\ncause was an Iniquitous banking and\ncurrency system, enacted In the Cool\nidge administration, which Its author\nand drafter recently denounced as \"a\nrelic of a bygone generation and no\nlonger adapted to our present-day busi\nness needs.\u201d which puts a premium on\nsavings deposit accounts by allowing\nbanks to offer alluring rates of Interest\nfor the 62-cent dollar. To add to that,\naided by the maladmini'tration of the\nFederal Reserve act, \u201ceconomy\u201d was\npreached day In and day out, with the\nresult that there are now nearly 53,-\n000,000 savings accounts In the United\nStates (before the World War there\nwere only 8.000,000) with total savings\namounting to nearly $30,000,000,000 at i\nrates of interest averaging nearly 4%\nper cent.\nAll recent financial reports, despite\nthe business depression, show that these\naccounts are dally Increasing. In New\nYork alone they reached nearly $250,-\n000,000 last year. As a result of these\nsavings there Is now nearly $300,000,000\nless cash In circulation than a year ago.\nEvery dollar put In these accounts\nmakes conditions so much worse, since\nthe misguided banker Is not lending the\nmoney to speculative business men be\ncause the purchasing power of the dol-\nI lar is not worth the interest demanded.\nEven at 2 per cent Interest business Is\nnot borrowing from the large financial\nInstitutions of the country, which are\nloaded with dollars because production\ncannot be consumed, due to the fact\nthat millions of men are out of em\nployment and their purchasing power\nhas been broken down. As a result of\nthis condition these big financial insti\ntutions jumped at the recent offer of\nthe Treasury Department to pay 2%\nper cent interest on Treasury certifi\ncates, the lowest rate offered since the\nCivil War, and it was more than four\ntimes oversubscribed. Recently the\nwriter asked this question: If in 1896\nthe year of the mythical gold standard\non which the world is supposed to be\ndoing business, when, as a matter of\nfact, it is doing business on banker\u2019s\ncredit\u2014and up to the entrance of the\nUnited States Into the World War one\ncould have borrowed a dollar which had\nmore than double the purchasing power\nof the present 62-cent dollar for 414\nper cent interest, how much Interest\nshould he be compelled to pay for the\npresent 62-cent dollar and why?\nThe Treasury Department officially\nanswers the question by allowing 2%\nper cent interest on its recent issue of\nTreasury certificates for the depreciated\ndollar\u2014all that it is worth.\nThere is no unemployment in France\ntoday, which is the most prosperous\ncountry In the world. In fact, latest\nreports show that 15,000 more men are\nneeded. The interest rate there is 2 per\ncent, and naturally money and credit\nis freely circulated, resulting in ample\nemployment for its people, as well as\nthe gold of the world flowing to It in\nreturn for its products. Nevertheless,\nthe United States holds mote than twice\nthe amount of gold held Dy France, the\nlatest figures of the Federal Reserve\nBeard showing that France holds 16.20\nper cent while the United States holds\n39.17 per cent, the remaining 45 per\ncent being distributed among the other\ncountries of the world, a totally dispro\nportionate percentage.\nDespite its large gold holdings, there\nis an abnormal business depress on in\nthe United States, wholly uncaged for,\nwhich requires a major operation to\ncut, out the cancer which caused the\nbusiness world to become sick. In the\nwriter\u2019s opinion, it will require\naround $2,000,000,000 of money and\ncredit to start the wheels of\ni industry revolving on a healthy\ni and permanent basts just one\nhalf the amount of credit deflated by\nthe maladministration of the Federal\nReserve Board in the recent Wall Street\ncrash. And since the world is burdened\nj with, interest\u2014rather, usury\u2014which it\nis unable to pay, it would be folly to\nask it further to burden itself. As a\nsay out of the dilemma, I suggest the\nenactment by Congress of the 25-year,\nnon-interest-bearing bond bill, now\npending in the Ways and Means Com\nmittee of the House of Representatives,\npermitting States, cities and counties,\nwhen giving propqr security, to deposit\ntheir bonds with the Secretary of the\nTreasury and receive legal tender money\nto start needed .public improvements\nwhich would absorb unemployment and\nincrease the purchasing power of the\ncountry until conditions became normal,\nwhen, by Executive order, it would be\nautomatically stopped.\nThen Congress should pass a new\nbanking and currency law prohibiting\nnational banks and trust companies\nfrom opening savings deposit accounts.\nThese accounts, since they are bought,\nare a real liability rather than an asset\nto the banks. Such accounts would\nl then seek the Government postal sav\nings banks, which pay 2 *l)er cent in\nterest, or the savings banks and build\ning and loan associations for invest\nment and when properly invested would\nyield a greater return in dividends than\nthe banks now pay In interest on such\ndeposits.\nHowever, since the woCd is supposed\nto be doing business on she mythical\ngold standard, and since the Increase\nj in the production of new gold through\nout the world is rapidly diminishing\n'and is insufficient to keep pace with the\ngrowing business of the world, it is\npalpably evident that the issue of 1896\n\u2014the bimetallic or quantitative theory\nof money\u2014will have to be fought again,\nnot as a political question, but as an\neconomic question, through interna\ntional agreement. Since the United\nStates holds nearly half the gold of\nthe world, that question is not as acute\nhere as in the rest of the world. But\nsuch condition materially affects the\nsale of the surplus products of the\nUnited States to foreign countries, be\ncause of the scarcity of gold in those\ncountries, on w\u2019hich, to some extent,\ndepends the internal prosperity of the\nUnited States. W. J. DWYER.\nStates Determine\nHolidays Observed\nFrom the New Orleans* States.\nA reader of the States writes to In\nquire if Columbus day was a national\nholiday. It wasn\u2019t. There is no such\nthing as a national holiday, not even\nthe Fourth of July, the day of the Dec\nlaration of Independence.\nNeither the President nor Congress,\nunder the Constitution, has the right\nto prescribe legal holidays in the various\nStates. That is one of the few rights\nthat have not been alienated from the\nStates. The Federal Government can\nmake holidays legal in the District of\nColumbia, and of course, if it chooses,\nit can close Government buildings all\nover the country on any day it pleases.\nBut that Is the limit of its authority.\nEvery year the President delivers a\nproclamation declaring a day of\nI Thanksgiving. Thanksgiving is ob-\nI served as a holiday in each of the 48\nStates, but not by the flat of the Presi\ndent. It becomes in a sense a national\nholiday only by concurrence of the\nStates, and any State, if it elected,\ncould pick some other day than that\nchosen by the President to offer thanks\nto Heaven for blessings received.\nFor commercial purposes the Federal\nGovernment in various acts of Congress\nhas recognized Labor day, Christmas,\nNew Year day, Washington\u2019s birthday.\nMemorial day and the Fourth of July as\npublic holidays. That is as far as the\nFederal Government can go. Inciden\ntally Memorial day is different in the\nSouth from that In the North.\nThe term \u201cnational legal holiday\u201d is\noccasionally loosely applied to holidays\nsuch as some of those mentioned above,\nwhich have been made legal holidays in\nevery State and In the District of Co\nlumbia, as Christmas for instance, and\nthey might be said to be national and\nlegal, but they become such not by any\naction of the Federal Government.\nI\" ANSWERS TO QUESTIONS\nr\nBY FREDERIC J. HASKIN.\nThis bureau does not give advice, but\nit gives free information on any sub\nject. Often, to be accurately informed\nIs to be beyond the need of advice, and\ninformation is always valuable, whereas\nadvice may not be. In using this serv\nice be sure to write clearly, state your\ninquiry briefly and inclose 2-cent stamp'\nfor reply postage. Address The Evening\nStar Information Bureau, Frederic J.\nHaskin, director, Washington, D. C. j\nQ. Is there a new edition of the game\nlaws for the 1930-31 hunting season?\u2014\nG. H. F.\nA. Game Laws, for the Season 1930-\n31, a booklet summarizing the pro\nvisions of Federal, State and provincial\nstatutes, is now ready for distribution.\nQ. Has a stamp bearing the portrait\nof William Howard Taft been made?\u2014\nA. C.\nA. A United States postage stamp\nbearing the portrait of former Presi\ndent William Howard Taft was placed\non sale June 4, 1930, at Cincinnati, 1\nt Ohio. The new stamp will have a 4-\ncent value.\nQ. What Federal highways run\nthrough Roanoke?\u2014B. V. C.\nA. Roanoke, Va., is on Federal high\nways 11 and 311.\nQ. Please give a list of the different\nphases and types of work connected\nwith the motion picture Industry.\u2014\nJ. N.\nA. There are at least 100 classifica\ntions of work in the Industry. Among\nthe more Important are actors, authors,\ndirectors, producers, cameramen, electri\ncians, continuity writers, painters, as\nsistant production managers, plasterers,\nsculptors, cytoonLsts, assistant direc\ntors, make-up artists, costumers, stars,\nfeatured players, character actors, \u201cex\ntras.\u201d riders, aviators, divers, auto\ndrivers, motor cyclists, iron workers, as\nsistant cameramen, art directors, archi\ntects, scenario editors, supervisors of\nproduction, title writers, casting direc\ntors, publicity men. interior decorators,\ncleaners, watchmen, motor truck' 1\ndrivers, gardeners, hairdressers, wig\nmakers, wood workers, firemen, engi\nneers, superintendents of plants, fore\nmen, musicians, draftsmen, film cutters,\ntinters, developers, printers, physicians,\nmetal workers, dressmakers, mechanics,\nreaders, errand boys, lawyers, washers,\nlaboratory managers, inspectors, ma\nchinists, telephone operators, shipping\nand receiving clerks, general sales\nmanagers, assistant salesmanagers, dis\ntrict salesmanagers, branch salesman\nagers. salesmen, inspectors, stenog\nraphers, postal clerks, clerks, wrappers,\nbookers, bookkeepers, exploitation man\nagers and assistants, projectionists, for\neign Managers and assistants, trans\nlators and newsreel editors and others.\nQ. Why do we call a bonfire by that\nname?\u2014V. D.\nA. Various derivations are given for\nthe word, among them boon-fire, con\nveying the idea that every one in the\nneighborhood contributes a portion of\nthe material for the fire.\nQ. How much money is spent in all\nkinds of advertising in this country each\nyear?\u2014D. C. B.\nA. The Editor and Publisher says the\nlatest reliable estimate is approximately\n$1,400,000,000 a year. Os this, about\n$450,000,000 is spent for newspaper\nspace by local advertisers: between\n$150,000,000 and $200,000,000 is spent\nfor classified advertising, and about\n$775,000,000 is spent by general or na\ntional advertisers, in newspapers, maga\nzines, billboards and signs, printed mat\nVergil, After 20 Centuries,\nLooms as Glorious Figure\nOn the 2,000 th anniversary of the\nLatin poet Vergil he to declared by the\nNew Orleans Item to be \u201cperhaps even\nmore alive at this time than he was In\nthe flesh,\u201d because \u201chis works \u00bbare more\nwidely read than they were even when\nhe Was at the height of his first fame\nin ancient Rome.\u201d American comment\nputs emphasis on the fact that while\nthis writer wanted hto work to be\nburned, as he believed it lacked perfec\ntion, it has greatly Influenced the de\nvelopment of thought and language. He\nis placed among the gianti.\n\u201cLike Shakespeare, like Dante, and\nlike all truly great writers throughout\nthe ages, the singer of \u2018Arms and the\nMan\u2019 wrote not for his own brief period\nalone, but for all time,\u201d says the Kala\n-1 mazoo Gazette. The Utica Observer-\nDispatch testifies that \u201cthose who hold\nthe Latih poets in high esteem have\nalways loved Vergil\u201d; that \"after the\nestablishment of Christianity, Constan\ntine the Great accepted his Fourth Ec\nlogue as a prophecy,\u201d and that \u201cwhen\nDante made his famous visit to Purga\ntory he chcse Vergil as his guide.\u201d\n\u201cHow many, remembering school\ndays, when they read Caesar\u2019s \u2018Com\nmentaries\u2019 before \u2018tackling\u2019 the\n\u2018Aeneid,\u2019 suggests the Oakland Tri\nbune, \u201cwill voice an opinion it is the\nlatter which remains in 'the mind, and j\neven above the eloquence of Cicero? i\n\u2018Praise a large domain, cultivate a small\nstate,\u2019 wrote Vergil 2,000 years ago. and\nin that there may be a thought for;\nMussolini.\u201d The Tribune declares \u2018there\nhave been mightier geniuses, but he\nlives in more hearts and minds.\u201d\n\n\u201cHe saw the majesty of man and was\nfilled with sadness that life is so fleet\ning and so crowded with frustration.\u201d\nthinks the Youngstown Vindicator, with\na tribute to the poet's message as \"of j\ndefinite value to the world today.\nThat paper continues: \u201cHis sense or\nthe illusion of life, the dignity of man\nstruggling against overwhelming odds\nI to conquer nature and himself, gives\nhis work a philosophical interest,\nwhich never ceases to attract the\nthoughtful. It is Vergil the philos\nopher who has put his thoughts into\nperfect poetry who lives and is *cele\nbrated today. He is loved for the i\npiety, the gravity and the sweetness of\nhis view of life. Farmers should make j\nhim their patron saint, for he spent j\nseven years on his \u2018\u2018Georgies,\u2019 a manual\nof farming, written in some of the most\nbsautiful 'poetry ever penned. The i\n\u2018Georgies\u2019 illustrates Vergil\u2019s nature.\nHe saw the dignity of farming, as he\nsaw the dignity of all of the common\ntasks by which man must live, and he\nstrove to show its nobility and the sat\nisfaction the farmer may take in his\nclose relationship with nature.\u201d\nLamenting Ow abandonment or\nfarms, the Columbia State looks upon\nthe great cities \u201ctrying in vain to shel\nter and feed the minions of a starving,\nmotley city-frenzied population\u201d and\nadds: \u201cVergil, on his father\u2019s farm and\non his own, and in his magnificent sing\ning poetry, dedicated to the tillers of\nthe soil, has a sharp lesson for us of\nthe world.\u201d\n\u201cWe do well to mark Vergil s bimil\nlenary advises the St. Louis Post-Dis\npatch. \u201cNone more than he belongs to\nthe ages.\u201d The Green Bay Press-\nGazette feels that \u201cit might surprise him\nto know how many high school young\nsters, in spite of dull class room routine,\nhave got a few thrills out of the\n\u2018Aeneid,* though he \u201cdid not write that\ngreat story for a text, book.\u201d The Press-\nGazette calls him \u201cone of the literary\ngiants of all time.\u201d\n\u201cWe would not say,\u201d according to the\nAtlanta Journal, \u201cthat the,, life and\nwork of this great poet have meant\nmore to the world than have the in\nvention of the steam engine, dis\ncovery and application of the power of\nelectricity and all the marvels and \u2022utili\nties of the age of the machine, for the\nvalues of the one are so essentially dif\nferent from those of the other that It\nwould be as pointless to compare them\nas to ask whether the stars or the\nwaves were of more moment to a wan\ndering mariner. But we do say that\nno performance of our industrial age,\nno heaoing up of perishable wealth\ncounts far a tithe as much in the\nprogress of the human spirit as the F\n..i\u2014\nter for direct advertising, broadcasting,\ntrade journals, farm publications, ear\ncards, etc.\nQ. How many pounds of flour does a\nbushel of wheat make?\u2014L. E. D.\nA. The Department of Agriculture\nsays that a bushel of wheat will yield\ni 40 to 42 pounds of flour, depending upon\nweight of the wheat.\nQ. Who invented barbed wire? \u2014P.\niO. W.\nA. The earliest patents for barbed\nwire fence were issued in 1874 to\nJoseph F. Glidden of De Kalb, 111., and\nfor the machine to manufacture it to\nGlidden and Phineas W. Vaughan.\nQ. Why was the Regency period in\narchitecture and furniture so named?\u2014\nK. L. J.\nA. The period of transition between\nLouis XIV and Louis XV was so named\nbecause at the time, 1715-23, France\nwas under the regency of Philip, Duke\nof Orleans.\nQ. Is there any proof that Betsy\nRoss actually made the first American\nflag?\u2014G H. W.\nA. The Betsy Ross legend was first\npresented in a psyper read before the\nHistorical Society of Pennsylvania in\n1870 by William J. Canby, a grandson\nof Betsy Ross. No contemporary docu\nments ir. support of the story have been\nfound, but there is no such evidence\ngiving the honor to any one else. It is\nknown that there was a Mrs. Ross liv\ning in Philadelphia at the time of the\nflag's adoption, and that she was an\nupholsterer and flagmaker by trade. Bhe\ndied January 30, 1836.\nQ. What are bank acceptances?\u2014N.\nB. C.\nA. The Federal Reserve Board de\nfines the bank acceptance as \u201ca draft\nor bill of exchange, whether payable in\nthe United States or abroad, and\nwhether payable in dollars or other\nmoney, of which the acceptor ia a bank\nior trust company, a firm, person, com\npany or corporation engaged generally\nin the business of granting bankers' ac\nceptance credits.\u201d\nQ. Do other breeds of horses, such as\nMorgans and American Baddlers. have\nthe blood of thoroughbreds in their\nveins?\u2014J. M.\nA. Almost all fine breeds of horses\nhave at some time been crossed with\nthoroughbreds.\nQ. What fa the Civic Forum Medal of\nHonor that is to be presented to Rear\nAdmiral Byrd? Who has received It\nin past years?\u2014D. W.\nA. This medal is awarded on the vote\nof the National Council of the forum,\nwhich fa composed of 100 leading citi\nzens In all parts of the country,. The\nmedal is 3Vs inches in diameter* It\nwus designed by Paul Manship in 1914,\nwhen It was first awarded to Gen.\nGoethals. Other recipients have been\nThomas A. Edison in 1915. Alexander\nGraham Bell in 1917. Herbert Hoover\nin 1920, Charles W. Eliot in 1923, Jean\nA. A. Jusserand, 1924, and Elihu Root,\n1927.\nQ. How many pounds will a cubic\nfoot of helium lift? From what is\nhelium made?\u2014F. B. S.\nA. The lifting power of helium 1$\n.069577 pounds per cubic foot. Helium\nis extracted from natural gas found In\nlarge quantities in Texas, Oklahoma\nand Wyoming. The process by which it\nis extracted fa a trade secret. Helium\nis found in small percentages, from 1 to\n2 per cent, in natural gas.\nfact that Vergil\u2019s poetry still is read\nand his memory still cherished.\u201d\na\n\u201cPerfection was his aim. Perfect\nwas his accomplishment. And now he\nlives after 2,000 y?ars,\u201d proclaims the\nMilwaukee Journal, and the Buffalo\nEvening News remarks: \u201cFortunately\nfor the memory of Vergil, the record la\nclear with regard to his life. It is not\nshrouded in mystery and in legend as\nis that of Homer of the Greks. For\ntunately, too, the Roman Emperor Au\ngustus declined to carry out the order\nof the dying poet that the \u2018Aeneid\u2019 be\ndestroyed\u2014a desire, based on a .fear of\nimperfection in his work, that gives a\nkeynote to the character of Vergil.\u201d\n\u201cAll English literature, from the time\nof Chaucer to the present, has exhibited\nevidences of the influence of Vergil,\u201d\ncomments the Walla? Walla Bulletin,\nwhile the Manchester Union offers the\nglowing tribute: \u201cNo poet that has\never lived hafeexerted a wider influence\nupon the thought and destiny of the\nhuman race. Shakespeare left an in\ndelible stamp upon English literature.\nGoethe is fitly regarded as the father\nof modem German literature, and\nDante of modern Italian. But these\nand other great poets of later times\nwho laid the foundations of the litera\ntures of their respective peoples may\nbe compared to the great Roman as\nmighty rivers are compared to the tiny\nspring from which they draw a common\nsource.\u201d\nAppropriateness of the celebration of\nthe event by the Alpha Chapter of Phi\nBeta Kappa at William and Mary Col\nlege, national home of that fraternity,\nis recognized by the Richmond News\nLeader in the description: \u201cThe stage,\nset with evergreens from the nearby\nwoods of the peninsula, framed mass-\nSlctures of which Morris Gest would not\nave been ashamed. The lighting\n1 heightened every picture. Hades was\nportrayed in its classic conception, not\n?s the domain of man\u2019s dark thought,\nbut as a place of punishment for his\ngrim misdeeds. The voices of the per\nformers. well trained, carried with re\nmarkable accuracy, and the pageant\nItself was so admirably phrased that a\nlong speech by old Anchlses held the\nauditors for 14 minutes. The music,\nwritten in Williamsburg by George M.\nSmall, and performed by the college\nband, deepened the illusion and was as\nmuch in the spirit of the piece as the\ntom-toms in \u2018Emperor Jones.\u2019\nI Nicaragua Honors\nSlain U. S. Marines\nFrom the New York Herald Tribune.\nTo our so-called anti-imperialists the\nspectacle of a Central American Presi\ndent awarding posthumous decorations\nto deceasea United States Marines muJt\nbe strangely disturbing. It is a picture\nwhich somehow does not fit the shallow\ndogmatism of those who depict the\nyoung men wearing the American uni\nform as mercenaries.\nYet this to exactly what recently hap\npened in Nicaragua, where the Presi\ndent, Senor Jose Maria Moncada,\nawarded posthumously the Nicaraguan\nMedal of Merit to 7 officers and\n32 enlisted men who lost their lives\nfighting for peace and freedom in that\ncountry. President Moncada. who lived\nthrough and took an active part in the\ndark days of 1927, is under no illusions\nas to the services which these young\nmen rendered his country. Although\nhe was then in open opposition to the\nNicaraguan government, he sees the\nconduct of these young Americana as\nsomething involving self-sacrifice and\nbravery of a ven high order. The\nnames of these m a now constitute a\nroll of honor in Nicaragua. As they\nalso died in the support of American\npolicies, their names -may well mean\nmuch to us.\nMore About Atterbury.\nFrom the Roanoke Times.\nGen. Atterbury\u2019s resignation as Re\npublican national committeeman from\nPennsylvania suggests that an attempt\nis to be made to railroad Hemphill into\nthe Governors chair. __\nf","height":"25428","width":"19827"}}
